DATA ANALYSIS OF THE RARE SOAY SHEEP

2024-01-10

The problem

The NAOs mean strength affects the survival of the rare soay sheep, potentially explained by weight changes. This study explores the impact of NAO and other variables on sheep weight and from the question it was evident that weight of the sheep is the response variable

Loading the data into Rstudio and modifiying based on requirements:

Both the tsv files were loaded by read.tsv function using readr package to the respective data frames.

describe() used to describe the data and year was found common in both files and the rest of the columns were altered accordingly to remove the missing values and sex data was altered to female with value 0 and male with value 1 for easy analysis.

A new column of just mean summer NAO and mean NAO of 12 months was created ,grouped by year and merged with the sheep_data to form a new dataframe merged_sheep_data

#here we are using merge.data.frame to merge the mean data with respect to years to plot the further data
merged_sheep_data <-  merge.data.frame(sNAO,na_drop_Sgroup, by= "year",all= TRUE) %>%
  merge.data.frame(mNAO,by="year",all=TRUE)%>%
  merge.data.frame(mweight,by="year",all=TRUE)

# Plot weight against mean NAO, grouped by year and subject ID
ggplot(merged_sheep_data, aes(x = mean_NAO, y = mean_weight, color = as.factor(year))) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +   # Scatter plot for each subject
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black") +  # Add trendline
  labs(
    title = "Relationship Between Weight and Mean NAO Over Years",
    x = "Mean NAO ",
    y = "Mean weight",
    color = "Year"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

we can see a slight slope increase trend in Meanweight in relation with MeanNAO over the years

NAO might explain some variations in weight, but it may not a strong predictor on its own, as implied by the spread of points around the line.

# Group the outlier data by 'ID' and summarize
outliers_by_ID <- outlier_data %>%
  group_by(ID) %>%  # Group by ID
  summarise(
    count = n(),                # Count of outliers per ID
    min_age = min(age, na.rm = TRUE),  # Minimum age when outlier occurred
    max_age = max(age, na.rm = TRUE),  # Maximum age when outlier occurred
    avg_weight = mean(weight, na.rm = TRUE)  # Average weight of outliers
  )

# Add a count column to represent the number of occurrences of each ID

  group_by(ID) %>%
  mutate(ID_count = n())  # Create a column that counts the number of occurrences of each ID

# Scatter plot with jitter and varying point size and shape based on ID
ggplot(outlier_data, aes(x = age, y = weight, color = as.factor(ID), size = ID_count, shape = as.factor(ID))) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, height = 0.2, alpha = 0.7) +  # Jitter to avoid overlap
  labs(

only weight has outliers, which can be visible through the boxplot, to further check if the outliers are data entry error or effect of other variables, i tried plotting the weight against age to check it and it seems that as the the age of few sheeps reaches 15-16 there seems to be increase in weight in some sheeps.As this data cannot be traced back and graph illustrates that the weight may not be entry error , thus now we can further conduct distribution of the response variable

Identyfying the potential error Distribution of response variable

#null hypothesis : there is no affect of summer NAO on the mean body mass of the sheep 

#error distribution 

#checking for NaN values
merged_sheep_data <- merged_sheep_data[!is.nan(merged_sheep_data$weight), ]

#fit the response variable to normal distribution
fit_gau <- fitdist(merged_sheep_data$weight,
                   distr = "norm",)

Response variable has been transformed to get better error distribution

#data transformation of response variable by log function
data_transformed <-   merged_sheep_data %>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  mutate(log_weight=log(weight))

#using the previous worked dataframe to add log response variable
alternative <-data_transformed %>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  mutate(mean_log_weight=mean(log_weight))
#fit the transformed response variable to normal distribution
fit_gau1 <- fitdist(data_transformed$log_weight,
                   distr = "norm")

Testing for autocorrelation

The graph and the p value of ljung_box_test says that its not significant

# Testing autocorrelation 
residuals_model_4 <- residuals(model4)

# Autocorrelation Function (ACFmodel4# Autocorrelation Function (ACF) Plot
acf(residuals_model_4, main = "ACF of Residuals")

# Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF) Plot
pacf(residuals_model_4, main = "PACF of Residuals")

# Ljung-Box Test
ljung_box_test <- Box.test(residuals_model_4, lag = 35, type = "Ljung-Box")
print(ljung_box_test)
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  residuals_model_4
## X-squared = 6434.7, df = 35, p-value < 2.2e-16
